<h1>Problem 899 - Original, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(ABC\) be a triangle with \(AB < AC\). Let \(\omega\) be a circle passing through \(B, C\) and
assume that \(A\) is inside \(\omega\). Suppose \(X, Y\) lie on \(\omega\) such that \(\angle BXA= \angle AYC\). Suppose also that \(X\) and \(C\) lie on opposite sides of the line \(AB\) and that \(Y\) and \(B\) lie on opposite sides of the line \(AC\). Show that, as \(X, Y\) vary on \(\omega\), the line \(XY\) passes through a fixed point.</p>
